   Yes, certainly within the Info Theory view for me.  +Tim O'Reilly
   When we receive info, even things such as our mood can come into play
   and add shades of nuance that we did not perceive before.
   Literature exists closer to Art than, say Science.  This gives the most
   freedom of interpretation, as it is often designed  to illicit
   reflection & emotion.  At the opposite end of the scale lies
   mathematics, the language of choice of the hard sciences, designed
   rather to keep emotions out.
   In storytelling in general, use of symbolism and analogy helps explain
   ideas in more personal ways.  Coming back to a book a decade or two
   later will give you a fresh perspective, as would the passing of
   generations and cultures.
   We take the info, and juxtapose it with our past experiences in the
   early stages, but later, time allows for interferences  to occur, when
   new info comes in changed by the past   that altered our focus or
   perspective.  Totally non-linear.
   Great literature, of course, makes analogies that everyone can
   immediately relate to, but it also layers info in such a way that we
   can't see the whole story at first glance.  I think that Great
   Education (or Journalism) would do the same.﻿
